openmediavault-oar (8.1.0~beta6-1) stable; urgency=medium

  * Delete now dismantles a pool independently of its GPT partition
    labels. It derives the tier arrays from the volume group's PVs and
    their members from the live block-device tree, so a pool whose labels
    are missing or wrong (e.g. one created before beta5) is still fully
    torn down -- arrays stopped, superblocks zeroed, disks wiped -- rather
    than leaving an assembled array and RAID metadata behind. Combined
    with beta5 this means a pre-beta5 pool can simply be deleted and
    recreated.
  * Restrict pool names to 24 characters. The GPT partition name field
    holds 36 UTF-16 units and the "oar@<pool>@t<NN>" label adds 8 chars of
    framing; a longer name was silently truncated by sgdisk, breaking
    discovery. The create form and RPC validation enforce the new limit.
  * Docs: note that a disk which previously held a filesystem should have
    that filesystem removed via Storage -> File Systems before it is added
    to a pool, so no stale /srv mount-point directory or mount-wait
    reference is left behind.

 -- carbrf <carbrf@gmail.com>  Mon, 06 Jul 2026 17:00:00 -0400

openmediavault-oar (8.1.0~beta5-1) stable; urgency=high

  * Critical: fix pool/tier discovery on real disks. GPT partition labels
    used ':' to separate the pool name and tier index
    (e.g. "oar:tank:t00"), but "sgdisk --change-name" splits its argument
    on EVERY colon, not just the one separating the partition number from
    the name -- it was silently truncating every on-disk label to just
    "oar". This meant partlabel-based disk/tier discovery never worked
    against real hardware for any pool created by this plugin: `status`
    and `detail` showed the pool as online but with empty disks/tiers
    lists, and grow/replace/scrub could not see any pool members. Unit
    tests never caught it because they exercise the Python layout model
    directly, never real sgdisk. Verified against GPT fdisk 1.0.9
    (Debian 12): every character other than ':' survives, including a
    live relabel of an already-assembled, in-use RAID member partition
    (no downtime, no resync, no data risk). The label format is now
    "oar@<pool>@t<NN>". A pool created by beta1-beta4 needs its member
    partitions relabeled once: for each member device and its tier index
    (see the tier's mdadm --detail Name=host:<pool>-t<NN> to identify
    both), run `sgdisk --change-name=<partnum>:oar@<pool>@t<NN> <disk>`
    -- this is a metadata-only change, safe on a live, in-use array.
    Newly created and grown pools are unaffected.

 -- carbrf <carbrf@gmail.com>  Mon, 06 Jul 2026 16:00:00 -0400

openmediavault-oar (8.1.0~beta4-1) stable; urgency=low

  * Package the Python modules with dh-python: bytecode is compiled on the
    target at install time and no stale __pycache__ is shipped.
  * Report each pool's mount point in the status and block deletion from
    the UI while the filesystem is mounted, not only while it is referenced
    by an fstab entry.
  * Housekeeping: tidy the notifyPool config-object assignment, correct the
    activity-summary docstring, bump Standards-Version to 4.6.2 and align
    the documented openmediavault dependency with debian/control.

 -- carbrf <carbrf@gmail.com>  Mon, 06 Jul 2026 15:00:00 -0400

openmediavault-oar (8.1.0~beta3-1) stable; urgency=low

  * Never leave a RAID5 tier without write-hole protection. During grow
    finalization the write-intent bitmap is dropped before PPL is
    restored; if re-enabling PPL fails, an internal bitmap is now re-added
    as a fallback instead of leaving the array unprotected.
  * Serialize pool finalization. The boot-time finalize unit, the per-pool
    finalize unit and the manual RPC can all target one pool; a per-pool
    lock now ensures only one runs the pvresize/lvextend/fs-grow/reap
    sequence at a time.
  * Ship the systemd units from /usr/lib/systemd/system and enable them,
    with a systemd daemon-reload, from the package maintainer scripts, so
    the on-demand finalize unit is always visible without a reboot.

 -- carbrf <carbrf@gmail.com>  Mon, 06 Jul 2026 14:00:00 -0400

openmediavault-oar (8.1.0~beta2-1) stable; urgency=low

  * Drop F2FS support. f2fs cannot be grown online, so the finalize step
    failed on the (mounted) pool a grow leaves behind and wedged the pool
    in the pending-finalize state. Supported file systems are now BTRFS,
    EXT4, XFS and JFS.
  * Replace/repair now reaps the retired disk. After a hot-replace or a
    repair, background finalization removes the old disk's stale array
    members, zeroes their superblocks and clears the OAR partition labels,
    so pool discovery no longer double-counts the replaced disk.

 -- carbrf <carbrf@gmail.com>  Mon, 06 Jul 2026 13:00:00 -0400

